	abstract = {The purpose of this study is to analyze the process through which the Soviet Union entered the war against Japan, occupied the northern half of Korea, and established a Soviet military government there in the name of a civil administration, and to examine its policies leading to the establishment of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
This study begins with an examination of Korea's modern international relations up to World War II, including Tsarist and Soviet involvement in Korea. Following that, Allied wartime negotiations on the Korean question are discussed, focusing on Stalin's goals in Korea. It then focuses on development of the Soviet occupation policy toward North Korea from the entrance of Soviet troops into North Korea to the withdrawal of its troops from North Korea in December 1948. The mechanisms the Soviets used to accomplish their goals in Korea and the role played by exogenous factors, such as U.S.-Soviet relations, in the formation of Soviet policy toward North Korea are examined particularly.
