Soviet Policy toward North Korea, from the beginning of Allied wartime negotiations through the establishment of the North Korean government, was marked by a kind of slash-and-burn strategy, indicating inconsistency and imprudence. Moscow had no clear design for Korea; instead, she pursued an ill-defined policy, attempting to maintain some influence over Korea while denying complete control over the peninsula to any one power.},
